**Introduction**

This guide walks you through setting up **Recruiter Outreach Automation** on Make.com.  
This automation monitors new recruiter/job entries in Google Sheets, enriches them with recruiter details and verified emails via Hunter.io, generates personalized outreach email with OpenAI, and then routes them send by Gmail Automatically along with resume. Also saves the generated emails into Google Docs and Updates Sheets for seamless documentation and communication.

![][image1]

**What You’ll Build**

A reusable Make.com scenario that:

* Watches for new recruiter/job entries in **Google Sheets**

* Sets multiple variables to fetch recruiter information to find email

* Uses **Hunter.io** to find and verify recruiter email addresses

* Retrieves resume details from **Google Docs** to give **Open AI** to generate personalized emails

* Leverages **OpenAI** to generate personalized outreach emails via recruiter details, resume, job description

* Routes the output to:

  * **Gmail** (to send automated emails)

  * **Google Docs** (for documentation and record keeping)

  * **Google Sheets** (to update rows with processed status)

**Step 1: Connect Google Sheets**

To start, you’ll need to set up a **Google Sheets Watch New Rows** module. This module will act as the trigger and monitor your sheet for any new recruiter/job entries.

1. **Add the Google Sheets Module**

   * In your Make.com scenario, click the **\+** button to add a new module.

   * Search for **Google Sheets** and choose **Watch New Rows**.

2. **Connect Your Google Account**

   * Click **Add** (if you don’t already have a connection).

   * Sign in with your Google account and grant the required permissions.

3. **Configure the Spreadsheet**

   * **Search Method** → Search by path

   * **Drive** → My Drive (or the correct Google Drive where your sheet is stored).

   * **Spreadsheet ID** → Select your spreadsheet (e.g., /Automation\_proj).

   * **Sheet Name** → Choose the sheet you want to monitor (e.g., Sheet1).

   * **Table contains headers** → Set to **Yes** (so the module uses the first row as headers).

   ![][image2]

4. **Save Settings**

   * Click **OK / Save**.

   * The Google Sheets module is now connected and ready to capture new rows automatically whenever recruiter/job data is added.

**Step 2: Prepare Recruiter Variables**

Before sending recruiter details to Hunter.io, we need to extract the recruiter’s **full name** from Google Sheets and make it available as a variable. This is required because Hunter.io needs the recruiter’s name to find their email.

1. **Add the Tools Module**

   * In your scenario, click the **\+** after the Google Sheets module.

   * Select **Tools → Set multiple variables**.

2. **Create a Variable**

   * Under **Item 1**, set:

     * **Variable name** → Full Name

     * **Variable value** → Map this to the recruiter’s name column from Google Sheets (e.g., Recruiter Name).

   ![][image3]

3. **Save the Module**

   * Click **Save** once your variables are defined.

**Step 3: Split Recruiter Full Name into First and Last Name**

In the next step, recruiter’s full name needs to be separated into two fields — **First Name** and **Last Name** — since Hunter.io requires both to locate an email address accurately.

1. **Add Another Tools Module**

   * Click the **\+** icon after your previous Tools module.

   * Select **Tools → Set multiple variables**.

2. **Create First Name Variable**

   Tool2 IMAGE![][image4]

   * Under **Item 1**, set:

     * **Variable name** → First Name

     * **Variable value** →

     * get( split( 4\. Recruiter Name (O) (J) ; space ) ; 1 )

   * This formula splits the recruiter’s full name by spaces and takes the **first part** as the first name.

3. **Create Last Name Variable**

   * Click **\+ Add item** to create a second variable.

   * Set:

     * **Variable name** → Last Name

     * **Variable value** →

     * get( split( 4\. Recruiter Name (O) (J) ; space ) ; 2 )

   * This formula extracts the **second part** of the name as the last name.

4. **Save Settings**

   * Click **Save** once both variables are set.

**Step 4: Hunter.io – Find an Email (connect & map fields)**

We’ll use **Hunter.io** to look up a recruiter’s email using the **company** plus the **first/last name** you created in the previous steps.

**1\) Create the Hunter connection (API key)**

1. Log in to **hunter.io** → go to **API** (from your avatar menu).

2. Copy your **API key**.

3. In **Make.com**, add a module → search **Hunter** → choose **Find an Email**.

4. Click **Add** next to *Connection*, paste your API key, and **save**.

**2\) Configure the action**

* **Search by** → By Company

* **Company** → map from Google Sheets (e.g., Company Name column).

* **First Name** → map the variable you created in **Tools** (e.g., First Name).

* **Last Name** → map the variable you created in **Tools** (e.g., Last Name).

* **Full Name** → (optional) map Full Name as well—Hunter can use it as a hint.

Hunter.io Module IMAGE![][image5]

**3\) Test & understand the output**

Click **Run once**. Successful runs typically return fields like:

* email

* score / confidence

* domain

* verification / status

**5\) Save**

Click **Save** to lock in your Hunter configuration.

**Step 5: Get Resume Content from Google Docs**

We’ll pull your resume text from **Google Docs** so OpenAI can use it to craft a personalized message.

1. **Add the Google Docs module**

* Click the **\+** after Hunter.io.

* Choose **Google Docs → Get Content of a Document**.

2. **Connect your Google account**

* Click **Add** next to *Connection*.

* Sign in and allow permissions.

* Select the connection you just created.

3. **Select the document**  
   You have two easy options:

* **By Dropdown** (shown in your screenshot)

  * **Choose a Drive** → My Drive (or the correct drive).

  * **Document ID** → pick your resume (e.g., Resume-Siza\_Kadri).

* **By URL / By ID** (if you prefer pasting a link)

  * Copy the Google Doc link of your resume.

  * Switch *Get Content of a Document* to **By URL** (or **By ID**) and paste it.

  ![][image6]

**Step 6: Set Up OpenAI (API key \+ email generation)**

**6.1 Get your OpenAI API key**

1. Sign in to your OpenAI account (Platform).

2. Go to **API Keys** and click **Create new secret key**.

3. Copy the key (you’ll only see it once).

Keep this private. Don’t put keys in your README or screenshots.

**6.2 Create the OpenAI connection in Make.com**

1. In your scenario, add a module: **OpenAI → Create a model response**.

2. In **Connection**, click **Add**, paste your API key, and **save**.

**6.3 Configure the OpenAI module**

* **Model** → o4-mini (system)

* **Prompt type** → Text prompt

* **Prompt** → paste the template below, then map fields from previous steps.

![][image7]

**Prompt to paste (then map):**

You are a professional career coach writing recruiter outreach emails. Your task is to draft a concise, professional cold email, no more than 250 words, to apply for the "{{4.\`0\`}}" position.

The email must leverage the candidate's information from the resume \[{{41.text}}\] and the job requirements from the {{4.\`8\`}} to demonstrate a strong, targeted fit as per the {{4.\`8\`}}

Key Requirements:

Opening: Start with a brief, compelling introduction that states the purpose.

Targeted Fit: Select and highlight 1-2 specific skills, experiences, or projects from the candidate's resume that directly align with the most important requirements in the job description.

Impact/Value: Briefly state the value the candidate can bring to the role or company.

Call to Action: Always use this sentence \["Looking forward to hearing from you\!"\]

Signature: Use a professional closing and the candidate's name from resume. NO LinkedIn link.

Ensure the tone is professional, confident, and persuasive. Do not use generic phrases; focus on quantifiable achievements or specific, relevant expertise.

Format Instructions:

\- Return the email body ONLY in \*\*HTML\*\* format.

\- Wrap each paragraph in \<p\>...\</p\>.

\- Insert a line break \<br/\> before the signature.

\- Do not include Markdown, explanations, or extra text.

Structure of the response:

\<p\>Dear {{4.\`9\`}},\</p\>

\<p\>\[Opening\]\</p\>

\<p\>\[Targeted Fit & Impact/Value\]\</p\>

\<p\>\[Call to Action\]\</p\>

\<p\>Best regards,\<br/\>  

Sizamayeen Kadri\</p\>

**Mappings used in the prompt (examples):**

* {{41.text}} → **Google Docs → Get Content** output (your resume text)

* {{4.\\0\`}}\` → **Job Title** from Google Sheets

* {{4.\\8\`}}\` → **Job Description / Key Requirements** from Google Sheets

* {{4.\\9\`}}\` → **Recruiter Name** from Google Sheets

**Recommended Advanced settings**

* Temperature: 0.5

* (Optional) Max output tokens: 800

**Step 7: Route the OpenAI Output (Docs archive \+ Gmail send)**

After OpenAI generates the HTML email, we **split the flow** with a **Router** so we can (a) save the message to Google Docs and (b) send it via Gmail.

**7.1Add a Router**

1. Click the **\+** after the **OpenAI** module.

2. Choose **Router**.

3. You’ll now create **two routes** from this Router:

   * **Route 1 — Google Docs (archive)**

   * **Route 2 — Gmail (send email)**

**7.2 Archive the OpenAI Email to Google Docs**

We’ll save the generated email into a Google Doc so you always have a record of what was sent.

1. **Add the module**

* Click **\+** after the OpenAI step.

* Choose **Google Docs → Insert a Paragraph to a Document**.

2. **Connect your Google account**

* In **Connection**, select your existing Google connection (or click **Add** and sign in).

3. **Select the target document**

* **Select a Document** → By Dropdown

* **Choose a Drive** → My Drive (or wherever the doc lives)

* **Document ID** → pick your archive doc (e.g., GPT output)

4. **Choose how to insert**

* **Insert a Paragraph** → By appending to the body of document  
  (This adds the new email at the end of the file.)

5. **Map the OpenAI result**

* **Appended Text** → map the OpenAI output from the previous step.  
  In your setup this is **34\. Result** (the HTML email the model produced).

6. Click **Save**.

![][image8]

![][image9]

7.3 Send the Email via Gmail

1) Add the Gmail Module  
* Click the second branch of the Router.  
* Choose Gmail → Send an Email.  
* Connect your Gmail account (if not already connected).  
* Configure Gmail Fields (refer to screenshots)  
* To: → map 4\. Email Found (U) (output from Hunter.io).  
* Subject: → Job Application for: 4\. Job Title (A).  
* Content: → map 34\. Result (OpenAI-generated HTML message).  
* Enable the “Use HTML content” toggle so that formatting is preserved.  
* Add Attachment  
* Enable Attachments → Map → Add item:  
* File name: for example Resume\_Siza.docx  
* Data: map 4\. RESUME (T) (from Google Docs → Get Content output)

**Step 8: Update Google Sheets with “Email Found” (and status)**

This route updates the **same row** that triggered the scenario with the email Hunter found, plus any tracking fields you want (confidence, status, timestamp).

**8.1 Add the module (on the Router’s third branch)**

* Click the **\+** on the Gmail module  and choose **Google Sheets → Update a Row**.

**8.2 Point to your sheet**

* **Connection** → your Google Sheets connection

* **Search Method** → Search by path

* **Drive** → My Drive (or the correct drive)

* **Spreadsheet ID** → select your file (e.g., /Automation\_proj)

* **Sheet Name** → Sheet1

* **Row number** → map the row from the **Watch New Rows** trigger (e.g., 4\. Row number)

  * This ensures you update the **exact same row** that started the run.

**8.3 Map only the columns you want to change**

Important: In **Update a Row**, only map the fields you intend to change—unmapped columns will stay as they are.

Typical mappings (examples from your setup):

* **Email Found (M)** → map **Hunter → Email** (e.g., 31\. Email)

**Save & test**

* Click **Save** and **Run once** on the whole scenario.

* Submit a test row to confirm:

  * Email column updates

  * Optional status fields update

  * The same row (not a new one) is modified
